		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">This summary covers only the main aspect of the proposal: an improved light detection system for biomedical imaging with less damage to living cells. INTRODUCTION: BIOMEDICAL FLUORESCENCE MICROSCOPYSome molecules can emit light  (photons) when they are exposed to light of a different color. This process is called fluorescence and the light emitted by the molecule represents its  fingerprint . This procedure can be used to gather specific information from a biological objects, such as living cells. It also allows to study chemical and genetic events or cancer on a molecular level within living cells. Biomedical fluorescence imaging, for example confocal laser scanning microscopy, has many applications in the life sciences. They include the development of new drugs and medications. In general this technique is very useful in medicine because it can monitor the response of a living cell to external stimulation (genetic, chemical or physical) on a molecular level.KNOWN PROBLEMSUnfortunatley, there are unwanted side effect of the biomedical imaging activity: the fluorescence excitation used in the imaging process does also influence the living cell and often damages it. Furthermore the excitation light can degrade the fluorescent markers itself, which leads to reduced signal and limits the observation time. In some cases, poor signal levels prevent the recording of useful data altogether. WHAT IS THE STRATEGY TO RESOLVE IT?One way to increase the overall efficiency of a biomedical microscope is to increase its photon detection quality, that is to make better use of the fluorescence light delivered by the optical part of the instrument. This allows to obtain the same information from the specimen at lower light levels, e.g. with less damage.The proposed research also covers a new type of photon detection unit which is predicted to be about 20 times more efficient compared to current technology, is patented and funded by the Royal Society. It will allow to obtain the same quality of information from biological specimens, where ligh levels 20 times lower can be used. Therefore the damage caused to the specimen during the imaging process will also be 20 times lower, which is a dramatic improvement.HOW DOES IT WORK?To understand the principle of the new light detection unit we need to consider fundamental principles of light detectors first. Any light detector is characterised by its quantum efficiency (QE) and the noise it produces. The QE denotes the fraction of the light that contributes to an electrical signal. Ideally this would be 100%.The noise is unwanted output from the detector. If a signal is not stronger than the noise, it cannot be detected.The standart light detector in current biomedical fluorescence instruments is a photon multiplier tube (PMT) and has a typical QE of 20% or below. A PMT also produces noise due to some intrinsic amplification process. Light can also be considered as a stream of particals, called photons. The ideal way to determine light intensity is thus to count photons. In this mode, the internal noise of the detector is cancelled. Unfortunately this mode is very slow. However, there are Avalanche photo diodes (APD) that have very good QE of 65% and operate in counting mode. However, they are too slow for standard biomedical imaging.The proposed idea is to split the light arriving at the detector into several beams of lower intensity. Several individual APD detectors are then combined in a detection unit where they count the arriving photons within the individual paths. Later the individual counts from several detectors are added to form the output signal of the unit. Parallel digital signal pprocessing, which creates no further noise, can be used. This way the proposed light detection unit combines superior quantum efficiency, low noise single photon counting and sufficient speed for biomedical imaging.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
